oc:kn_06a24758 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When presenting all critique findings" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never give vague or generic feedback. Always name the specific element (e.g., 'the submit button', not 'some elements'), explain why it matters to users, give concrete fix suggestions, and tag with P0–P3 severity." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Vague feedback wastes time and is not actionable; developers need honest, specific, prioritized input to ship great design" ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_1b3b223b a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When evaluating Information Architecture & Cognitive Load dimension" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Run the 8-item cognitive load checklist from the reference: single focus, chunking (≤4 items/group), grouping, visual hierarchy, one thing at a time, minimal choices (≤4 visible options), working memory (no cross-screen recall), progressive disclosure. Score: 0–1 failures = low, 2–3 = moderate, 4+ = critical." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Cognitive overload directly causes user errors, frustration, and abandonment — it is the most measurable predictor of UX failure" ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_2a00f08c a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Always, as the first dimension of critique evaluation" ;
    oc:directiveContent "AI Slop Detection is the most critical check — review the design against all DON'T guidelines in frontend-design to identify fingerprints of AI-generated work (gradient text, glowing accents, glassmorphism, identical card grids, hero metric layouts, generic fonts). If it looks AI-made when called out, it fails." ;
    oc:hasRationale "AI-generated interfaces all share recognizable patterns that make them feel generic and inauthentic; catching these is the highest-priority quality gate" ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_48768a37 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:OutputFormat ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When presenting critique findings in Phase 2 and Phase 4" ;
    oc:directiveContent """## Design Health Score
| # | Heuristic | Score | Key Issue |
|---|-----------|-------|-----------|
| 1–10 | {Heuristic Name} | {0–4} | {specific finding or —} |
| **Total** | | **{score}/40** | **{Rating band}** |

## Anti-Patterns Verdict
{Pass/Fail}: {specific AI-generated tells}

## Overall Impression
{Gut reaction — what works, what doesn't, single biggest opportunity}

## What's Working
{2–3 specific things done well}

## Priority Issues
- **[P?] {What}**: {Why it matters}. Fix: {concrete suggestion}. → `/{command}`

## Persona Red Flags
**{Persona Name}**: {Specific element-level red flags}. ⚠️ {risk assessment}

## Minor Observations
{Quick notes}

## Recommended Actions
1. `/{command}` — {context-specific description}
...
N. `/polish` — Final quality pass""" ;
    oc:templateVariables "Heuristic Name",
        "Key Issue",
        "Persona Name",
        "Rating band",
        "Score",
        "What",
        "Why it matters",
        "command",
        "concrete suggestion",
        "risk assessment" .

oc:kn_76c78bde a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:WorkflowStrategy ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When running persona-based testing" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Select 2–3 personas most relevant to the interface type using the selection table in personas.md. Walk through the primary user action as each persona and report specific red flags naming exact elements that fail — not generic concerns." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Different user archetypes expose different failure modes that a single design-director perspective would miss" ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_847354df a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When scoring Design Health in Phase 2" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Be honest with Nielsen heuristic scores — a 4 means genuinely excellent. Most real interfaces score 20–32 out of 40. Use the 0–4 scoring rubric from the heuristics-scoring reference for each of the 10 heuristics." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Inflated scores undermine the value of the critique and hide real problems from the team" ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_a76453f8 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When generating Phase 4 action recommendations" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Only recommend commands from the approved set: /animate, /quieter, /optimize, /adapt, /clarify, /distill, /delight, /onboard, /normalize, /audit, /harden, /polish, /extract, /bolder, /arrange, /typeset, /critique, /colorize, /overdrive. Skip commands addressing zero issues. Always end with /polish if any fixes recommended. Respect user's scope and off-limits areas." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Ensures recommendations are executable within the skill ecosystem and aligned with the user's stated constraints" ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_e3db6048 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Prerequisite ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before starting any critique" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Invoke /frontend-design first for design principles, anti-patterns, and the Context Gathering Protocol. If no design context exists, run /teach-impeccable before proceeding. Also gather what the interface is trying to accomplish." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Design context provides the project-specific audience, brand, and style guardrails that make critique relevant rather than generic" ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_f0db659b a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When formulating user questions in Phase 3" ;
    oc:directiveContent "In Phase 3 questions: every question must reference specific findings from Phase 2, never ask generic questions. Keep to 2–4 questions max. Offer concrete options not open-ended prompts. If findings are straightforward (1–2 clear issues), skip questions entirely and go to Phase 4." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Generic questions waste user time and produce unhelpful answers; findings-specific questions yield actionable direction" ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_f1c1d762 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Every critique execution" ;
    oc:directiveContent "1. Run /frontend-design and gather design context (run /teach-impeccable if none exists) 2. Evaluate across 10 dimensions: AI Slop Detection (critical), Visual Hierarchy, Info Architecture & Cognitive Load, Emotional Journey, Discoverability & Affordance, Composition & Balance, Typography, Color with Purpose, States & Edge Cases, Microcopy & Voice 3. Present findings: Design Health Score (Nielsen 0–4 × 10 heuristics), Anti-Patterns Verdict, Overall Impression, What's Working (2–3 items), Priority Issues (3–5 with P0–P3 severity), Persona Red Flags (2–3 personas), Minor Observations 4. Ask user 2–4 targeted questions referencing specific findings (priority direction, design intent, scope, constraints) 5. Present recommended command actions mapped to issues, ordered by user priority, ending with /polish" ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

_:ref_03aabd7f527cbd8c a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description "**`/command-name`** — Brief description of what to fix (specific context from critique findings)" ;
    oc:blockType "workflow_step" ;
    oc:stepId "step_1" ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

_:ref_26340c0813c30f0e a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description "**Constraints** (optional — only ask if relevant): If the findings touch many areas, ask if anything is off-limits. For example: \"Should any sections stay as-is?\" This prevents the plan from touching things the user considers done." ;
    oc:blockType "workflow_step" ;
    oc:stepId "step_4" ;
    oc:stepOrder 4 .

_:ref_d12f4f88f8b23ddc a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description "**Design intent**: If the critique found a tonal mismatch, ask whether it was intentional. For example: \"The interface feels clinical and corporate. Is that the intended tone, or should it feel warmer/bolder/more playful?\" Offer 2–3 tonal directions as options based on what would fix the issues found." ;
    oc:blockType "workflow_step" ;
    oc:stepId "step_2" ;
    oc:stepOrder 2 .

_:ref_e8938bdce7906e35 a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description "**Priority direction**: Based on the issues found, ask which category matters most to the user right now. For example: \"I found problems with visual hierarchy, color usage, and information overload. Which area should we tackle first?\" Offer the top 2–3 issue categories as options." ;
    oc:blockType "workflow_step" ;
    oc:stepId "step_1" ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

_:ref_f5126ba455bf0350 a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description """**`/command-name`** — Brief description (specific context)
...""" ;
    oc:blockType "workflow_step" ;
    oc:stepId "step_2" ;
    oc:stepOrder 2 .

_:ref_fae72896da10b986 a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description "**Scope**: Ask how much the user wants to take on. For example: \"I found N issues. Want to address everything, or focus on the top 3?\" Offer scope options like \"Top 3 only\", \"All issues\", \"Critical issues only\"." ;
    oc:blockType "workflow_step" ;
    oc:stepId "step_3" ;
    oc:stepOrder 3 .

_:ref_5aa82e2d6e94ef37 a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description "Ask 2–4 targeted questions based on specific findings (priority direction, design intent, scope, constraints). Skip if findings are straightforward." ;
    oc:expectedOutcome "User priorities, scope, and constraints clarified" ;
    oc:stepDependsOn _:ref_ad577f0ae55d62f9 ;
    oc:stepId "ask-user" .

_:ref_78de331b2136d2e3 a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description "Invoke /frontend-design, gather design context (run /teach-impeccable if none exists), understand what the interface is trying to accomplish" ;
    oc:expectedOutcome "Design context loaded, interface purpose understood" ;
    oc:stepId "prepare" .

_:ref_874a6f9d27be074f a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description "Evaluate interface across 10 dimensions: AI Slop Detection, Visual Hierarchy, Information Architecture & Cognitive Load (run 8-item checklist), Emotional Journey, Discoverability & Affordance, Composition & Balance, Typography, Color with Purpose, States & Edge Cases, Microcopy & Voice" ;
    oc:expectedOutcome "Structured findings across all 10 dimensions with specific issues identified" ;
    oc:stepDependsOn _:ref_78de331b2136d2e3 ;
    oc:stepId "evaluate" .

_:ref_ad577f0ae55d62f9 a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description "Present Design Health Score (Nielsen heuristics table), Anti-Patterns Verdict, Overall Impression, What's Working, Priority Issues (3–5 with P0–P3), Persona Red Flags (2–3 personas), Minor Observations" ;
    oc:expectedOutcome "Complete scored critique with specific, actionable findings" ;
    oc:stepDependsOn _:ref_874a6f9d27be074f ;
    oc:stepId "present-findings" .

